1) Prove Git is actually using the proxy

Check Git’s proxy config at all levels:

git config --show-origin --get-regexp 'http\.(proxy|httpsProxy|noProxy|sslVerify|sslCAInfo|version)'


Also check environment proxy vars (Git/curl will honor these too):

env | egrep -i 'http_proxy|https_proxy|all_proxy|no_proxy'


If both are set, you can get inconsistent behavior. Pick one approach (Git config or env vars) and keep it consistent.

Quick forced test (overrides everything for one command):

git -c http.proxy=http://proxy.host:port clone <repo_url>

2) Validate the proxy can CONNECT to your Git host

If you’re cloning via HTTPS, the proxy must support CONNECT to 443.

Run:

# Replace host with your git host (e.g., github.com, git.company.com)
curl -v --proxy http://proxy.host:port https://<git_host>/ -o /dev/null


If this resets, it’s not a “Git” problem — it’s proxy policy/auth/SSL inspection, or it can’t tunnel reliably.

If your proxy requires auth:

curl -v --proxy http://user:pass@proxy.host:port https://<git_host>/ -o /dev/null

3) Turn on Git + curl trace and look for the exact reset moment
GIT_TRACE=1 GIT_TRACE_CURL=1 GIT_CURL_VERBOSE=1 \
git clone <repo_url> 2>&1 | tee /tmp/git-proxy-debug.log


In the log, pay attention to:

CONNECT <git_host>:443 result

Any Proxy-Authenticate: challenges (407 issues)

TLS handshake lines (SSL inspection/certs)

Whether it resets during pack download (long-lived tunnel drops / idle timeouts)

4) Force HTTP/1.1 (common proxy compatibility fix)

A lot of corporate proxies + HTTP/2 = random resets.

git config --global http.version HTTP/1.1
git clone <repo_url>


(You can undo later with git config --global --unset http.version.)

5) If your org does SSL inspection, fix CA trust (don’t disable SSL long-term)

If the proxy is doing TLS interception, your machine needs the corporate root CA trusted by Git/curl.

Check if Git is verifying and which CA bundle it uses:

git config --global --get http.sslVerify
git config --global --get http.sslCAInfo


If curl works only with -k or Git works only with http.sslVerify=false, you likely need to point Git at the corp CA bundle:

git config --global http.sslCAInfo /path/to/corp-root-ca.pem


(Your IT/security team typically provides that PEM.)

6) Avoid proxy credential problems (407 / auth method)

If proxy auth is flaky, make it explicit in Git:

git config --global http.proxy http://user:pass@proxy.host:port
git config --global http.proxyAuthMethod basic


If your password has special characters, URL-encode it (common hidden cause of weird resets).

7) If you’re cloning over SSH, that’s a different proxy story

SSH doesn’t automatically use HTTP proxies. If your repo URL is git@host:org/repo.git, you either need:

direct SSH allowed outbound, or

SSH over HTTPS, or

a ProxyCommand (e.g., nc / corkscrew) approved in your environment

Quick check:

ssh -vvvT git@<git_host>


If it resets immediately, SSH is probably blocked and you should use HTTPS cloning via the proxy instead.

8) Proxy drops long downloads: try shallow clone + reduce compression

If it resets partway through large repos:

git clone --depth 1 <repo_url>
git config --global core.compression 0


If shallow succeeds but full fails, it’s very consistent with proxy idle/size/time limits.

Most useful next data (paste back)

If you paste:

output of git config --show-origin --get-regexp 'http\.(proxy|httpsProxy|noProxy|version|ssl.*)'

output of curl -v --proxy http://proxy.host:port https://<git_host>/ -o /dev/null (redact creds)

the last ~40 lines of /tmp/git-proxy-debug.log around the reset

…I can tell you whether it’s auth (407), TLS inspection/CA, HTTP2/proxy incompatibility, or tunnel drops/timeouts.
